heading_context: If you got your licence before 1 January 1997
chunks.html_content:
You can tow trailers up to a certain weight with your car driving licence. The weight you’re allowed to tow depends on when you got your licence.

You’ll need to know the weight of both the vehicle and trailer - also known as the ‘maximum authorised mass’ (MAM).

The MAM is listed in the owner’s manual and is normally shown on a plate or sticker fitted to the vehicle or trailer.

You can usually drive a vehicle and trailer with a combined weight of up to 8,250kg MAM. View your driving licence information to check.

You’re also allowed to drive a minibus with a trailer over 750kg MAM.

heading_context: If you got your licence from 1 January 1997
chunks.html_content: You can tow a trailer that weighs up to 3,500kg MAM.
chunks.plain_content:

If you got your licence from 1 January 1997
You can tow a trailer that weighs up to 3,500kg MAM.

chunks.html_content:
You can get training on how to tow a trailer safely, including caravans or horse boxes.

You can find a training provider or course through:

  • National Register of LGV Instructors
  • Safe Towing Scheme
  • Skills for Logistics

Check with the provider on the type of training they offer and the cost.

heading_context: Towing heavier vehicle and trailer combinations
chunks.html_content:
To tow combinations that are heavier than what’s allowed by your current licence, you need to:

  1. Apply for a provisional licence for a medium-sized lorry and trailer (category C1+E).

  2. Pass the lorry theory test.

  3. Pass the C1+E driving test
chunks.plain_content:

Pass the lorry theory test.

heading_context: Towing heavier vehicle and trailer combinations
chunks.html_content: You need to take extra Driver Certificate of Professional Competence (CPC) tests if driving the medium-sized lorry is the main part of your job.

heading_context: Towing heavier vehicle and trailer combinations
chunks.html_content: Once you’ve done this you can drive vehicles and trailers with a combined weight of up to 12,000kg MAM.
chunks.plain_content:
Towing with a car
Towing heavier vehicle and trailer combinations
Once you’ve done this you can drive vehicles and trailers with a combined weight of up to 12,000kg MAM.

chunks.html_content:
Most cars have a maximum weight they can tow. It’s usually listed in the handbook or specification sheet.

Alternatively the vehicle’s ‘gross train weight’ may be listed on the vehicle identification number (VIN) plate on the car. This is normally under the bonnet or inside the driver’s door.
chunks.plain_content:
Towing with a car
Most cars have a maximum weight they can tow. It’s usually listed in the handbook or specification sheet.
Alternatively the vehicle’s ‘gross train weight’ may be listed on the vehicle identification number (VIN) plate on the car. This is normally under the bonnet or inside the driver’s door.

chunks.html_content: The gross train weight is the weight of the fully-loaded car plus fully-loaded trailer and must not be exceeded.
chunks.plain_content:
Towing with a car
The gross train weight is the weight of the fully-loaded car plus fully-loaded trailer and must not be exceeded.

chunks.html_content:
If your VIN plate does not list a train weight, you should not use your vehicle for towing.

The maximum trailer width for any towing vehicle is 2.55 metres.
chunks.plain_content:
Towing with a car
Maximum width
If your VIN plate does not list a train weight, you should not use your vehicle for towing.
The maximum trailer width for any towing vehicle is 2.55 metres.

chunks.html_content:
If your vehicle’s maximum authorised mass (MAM) is 3,500kg or less, you cannot tow a trailer that’s longer than 7 metres.

If your vehicle’s MAM is more than 3,500kg then the maximum lengths are:

  • 12 metres for the trailer towed by the vehicle
  • 18 metres for the vehicle and trailer combined
  • 3.05 metres for how far the load can overhang the back of the trailer (whatever the length of the trailer is)

Maximum lengths do not include the A-frame (the frame that connects your car to the trailer).
chunks.plain_content:
Towing with a car
Maximum length
If your vehicle’s maximum authorised mass (MAM) is 3,500kg or less, you cannot tow a trailer that’s longer than 7 metres.

  18 metres for the vehicle and trailer combined
  3.05 metres for how far the load can overhang the back of the trailer (whatever the length of the trailer is)

Maximum lengths do not include the A-frame (the frame that connects your car to the trailer).

chunks.html_content:
The equipment you use with your trailer or caravan must:

  • meet certain safety standards
  • be used correctly
chunks.plain_content:
Towing with a car
The equipment you use with your trailer or caravan must:

  meet certain safety standards
  be used correctly

chunks.html_content: You can be fined up to £2,500, be banned from driving and get 3 penalty points for using a vehicle in a dangerous condition.
chunks.plain_content:
Towing with a car
You can be fined up to £2,500, be banned from driving and get 3 penalty points for using a vehicle in a dangerous condition.

chunks.html_content:
Carry out safety checks to make sure you’re using the trailer and equipment legally.

If you get a tow bar for your car, it needs to be ‘type approved’. This means it meets EU regulations and is designed for your car.

Type-approved tow bars have a label with:

  • an approval number
  • details of the vehicles it’s approved for
chunks.plain_content:

chunks.html_content: If your car was first used before 1 August 1998, your tow bar does not need to be type-approved.

chunks.html_content:
You must have an adequate view of the road behind you.

Fit suitable towing mirrors if your trailer or caravan is wider than the rear of your car.
chunks.plain_content:
Towing with a car
Towing mirrors
You must have an adequate view of the road behind you.
Fit suitable towing mirrors if your trailer or caravan is wider than the rear of your car.

chunks.html_content: You can be fined up to £1,000 and get 3 penalty points for towing without proper towing mirrors.
chunks.plain_content:
Towing with a car
Towing mirrors
You can be fined up to £1,000 and get 3 penalty points for towing without proper towing mirrors.

chunks.html_content: Your trailer must have a working brake system if it weighs over 750kg when it’s loaded.
chunks.plain_content:
Towing with a car
Trailer or caravan brakes
Your trailer must have a working brake system if it weighs over 750kg when it’s loaded.

chunks.html_content: Some smaller trailers also have brakes, but these are optional.
chunks.plain_content:
Towing with a car
Trailer or caravan brakes
Some smaller trailers also have brakes, but these are optional.

chunks.html_content:
Any brakes must be in good working order.

You must use a breakaway cable or secondary coupling in case the trailer becomes detached from your car. Carry out safety checks.
chunks.plain_content:
Towing with a car
Trailer or caravan brakes
Any brakes must be in good working order.
You must use a breakaway cable or secondary coupling in case the trailer becomes detached from your car. Carry out safety checks.

chunks.html_content:
You must display the same number plate on your trailer as on your towing car.

If you tow more than one trailer at a time, fix the number plate to the trailer at the back.
chunks.plain_content:
Towing with a car
Number plates
You must display the same number plate on your trailer as on your towing car.
If you tow more than one trailer at a time, fix the number plate to the trailer at the back.

chunks.html_content:
American trailers and caravans do not always meet European safety regulations.

If you want to use an American caravan or trailer in the UK or the EU, you must first check that it’s legal.

Read more about brakes and couplings for American caravans and trailers.
